Luca, Steve Schoger here with my visual design review. The backend logic looks solid -- session-aware redirect, correct status code, good test coverage. But there are **blocking visual design issues** I need resolved before I can consent.

## Blocking Issue: Missing CSS

The `.btn`, `.btn--primary`, and `.btn--secondary` classes used in `index.html` have **no CSS definitions** anywhere in `main.css`. Right now, the "Create account" and "Sign in" links render as plain unstyled anchor tags -- blue underlined text sitting side by side with no visual hierarchy, no spacing, and no differentiation between primary and secondary actions.

This violates our Definition of Done:
- "Visual hierarchy is clear -- one primary focal point per screen"
- "Visual design follows the established design token system"

## Blocking Issue: No Layout/Centering

The content block has no centering or spacing wrapper. The `<h1>`, `<p>`, and `<nav>` will sit flush-left in the container at full width. This is inconsistent with our auth pages, which use `max-inline-size: 24rem; margin-inline: auto` for centered, focused layouts.

## What Needs to Change

### 1. Template Structure
Wrap the content in a centered hero container and stack the CTAs vertically:

```html
<div class="landing-hero">
    <h1>Welcome</h1>
    <p>Keep track of what you need to do.</p>
    <nav aria-label="Get started">
        <a href="/register" class="landing-hero__cta">Create account</a>
        <p class="landing-hero__alt">Already have an account? <a href="/login">Sign in</a></p>
    </nav>
</div>
```

### 2. CSS to Add (in the components layer)

```css
/* ---- Landing Hero ----
 * Centered welcome content for unauthenticated visitors.
 * Matches the 24rem center-axis used by auth forms. */
.landing-hero {
    max-inline-size: 24rem;
    margin-inline: auto;
    padding-block-start: var(--space-3xl);
    text-align: center;
}

.landing-hero h1 {
    margin-block-end: var(--space-sm);
}

.landing-hero p {
    color: var(--color-fg-muted);
    font-size: var(--font-size-lg);
    margin-block-end: var(--space-xl);
}

.landing-hero__cta {
    display: block;
    inline-size: 100%;
    padding-block: var(--space-sm);
    padding-inline: var(--space-md);
    font-size: var(--font-size-base);
    font-weight: var(--font-medium);
    line-height: var(--leading-tight);
    text-align: center;
    text-decoration: none;
    color: white;
    background-color: var(--color-primary);
    border-radius: var(--radius-md);
    margin-block-end: var(--space-md);
}

.landing-hero__cta:hover {
    background-color: var(--color-primary-dark);
    color: white;
}

.landing-hero__alt {
    font-size: var(--font-size-sm);
    color: var(--color-fg-muted);
}
```

### Why This Approach

1. **One primary action** -- "Create account" is the full-width blue button, immediately scannable as the thing to do.
2. **Secondary action subordinated** -- "Sign in" is a small text link below, clearly secondary. Returning users will find it; new users won't be confused by two equal-weight choices.
3. **Consistent center-axis** -- 24rem matches auth forms, so the flow from landing -> register feels cohesive.
4. **Token-only values** -- every property references design tokens. No hardcoded pixels or colors.
5. **No `.btn` utility classes** -- We don't have a generic button utility system, and we shouldn't create one just for this. The `landing-hero__cta` is a component-scoped style, consistent with our BEM-ish naming.

### Non-Blocking Notes
- The copy "Keep track of what you need to do." is good -- clear, scannable, no happy talk.
- "Welcome" as the `<h1>` is fine, though I'd also be happy with something more direct like "Get things done." -- I'll defer to Marty and Steve Krug on copy.

I cannot consent until the CSS is in place and the template uses a proper centered layout. Everything else about the implementation looks good.

